Rating: 4
I found this a recipe I would make again, but with subtle changes. Definitely agree about salt. I did not add much and the soy sauce made it sufficiently salty. Also, I had about 2.5 pounds of boneless country style beef ribs (from Walmart--yes, Walmart--limited options here in southcentral KY!). So I halved the recipe. I did not have fresh ginger so used a heaping teaspoon of powdered ginger. Also, added honey in lieu of sugar and a heaping tablespoon full of this marmalade I had with large shreds of orange rind. Finally, I made it in my 4 quart covered Le Creuset and braised the ribs on both sides for about 3 minutes a side on very high heat in a bit of oil. Then I prepared the glaze in a separate pot and poured it over the ribs, put the foil on, then the lid, and cooked as instructed. I was glad and surprised when I took it out and the glaze had reduced on its own to a lovely, thick, syrup. I served the ribs with brown rice and steamed broccoli. Definitely a HIT!! The only thing I would do differently next time is to add a bit more sweetener, perhaps more honey, to have the fresh ginger on hand, and to not use any salt at all. Check out my food/pantry-related (and other topics) blog at www.InthePantry.blogspot.com Catherine S. Pond, author of THE PANTRY-Its HISTORY & MODERN USES [Gibbs Smith: 2007]

