I followed the good advice of several reviews and left out the salt and used low sodium soy sauce. Instead of fresh orange juice, I used thawed frozen orange juice concentrate. I thought it would add more of an orange taste. After braising the pork for two hours, I poured the liquid into a pot to reduce after removing as much fat on top as I could. I periodically tasted the liquid while it was reducing, I found I wanted a sweeter taste. So, I added an additional tablespoon of sugar and three heaping tablespoons of orange marmalade. The resulting sauce was great! Next time I plan to add chili flakes to spice up the flavor!

Rating: 4
I made this last night with country style pork ribs. After reading all the reviews I did not salt the ribs. I always use low- sodium soy sauce but I did not use as much as the recipe called for. I only had a little over 1 pound of ribs so I only used 1/4 amount of ingredients except for the orange juice--I used 1 cup (not fresh, didn't have any oranges). I sprinkled the ribs with black pepper and Chinese 5 spice powder and browned in olive oil. I then sauted some chopped onions along with the garlic and ginger and then added the rest of the sauce ingredients. I had a bottle of Ken's Sesame Ginger marinade so I added a tablespoon of that and a splash of rice vinegar. After braising for 2 hours I removed the ribs and reduced the sauce, adding a splash of sake which added a great flavor. I then brushed the ribs with the glace and put under the broiler for a few minutes. They were great! I served with steamed white rice, broccoli and carrots. Will make again for sure. I'm also going to try the sauce with different types of pork...definitely a keeper!

