Rating: 4
This is one of those timeless recipes with lots of integrity on its own but plenty of possibilities for variations. Letting a tiny bit of steam escape meant that by the end of the cooking time the liquid in the pan was already the consistency of a glaze--a rich, dark, caramel sauce that one could scrape from the corners of the pan. For interest, I plan to add some Chinese five spice powder or broken up star anise or cinnamon sticks. Or maybe some lime juice in with the orange juice. Given that the oven was hot for 2 hours, I roasted some potatoes and other root vegetables. And I made an Asian slaw with more ginger, garlic, and some peanutes puréed in the blender with lime juice. Was a great side for the hearty but somewhat mild pork.

